In 2009, President Mohamed Nasheed resigned when a revolt erupted and political unrest escalated. This was fourteen months into his five year term of office in which he promised tamp down corruption and bring political freedoms to the people of Maldives.

Following Nasheed’s resignation, a national Search Committee conducted a search for a new president of maldives. The committee’s search led to the emerging of Mohammed Waheed Hassan Manik, a member of the Judicial Service Commission, as the interim President. The newly appointed President Waheed also became the long-serving Vice President.

While this might have brought back the much-desired political stability, it was a hollow victory for the people of the archipelago as it has proved difficult to achieve genuine reconciliation among the country’s political leaders. A struggle between a genuine democratic government and a local oligarchy that exercises influence in the media remains ongoing.

Oddly, after making such a big step forward, the people of Maldives witnessed the President giving full support to the Gambling industry of Maldives, when he delivered a speech in support of the government, hailing its stupendous victory in making gambling legal in the country.
